01:40:31,100 --> 01:40:35,103
-Did the sound frighten you?
-Very much.

1431
01:40:35,271 --> 01:40:37,937
Did you close your eyes?

1432
01:40:39,439 --> 01:40:42,647
At first...until the shooting stopped.
Then I opened them.

1433
01:40:42,939 --> 01:40:46,941
Did you think the men who were shooting
were going to kill everybody in McHale's?

1434
01:40:47,317 --> 01:40:51,026
Well, I really didn't know what to think.
I just knew that the man had been shot.

1435
01:40:51,443 --> 01:40:55,778
Did you think you might be shot dead
by the two cold-blooded killers?

1436
01:40:56,986 --> 01:40:58,320
Yes, I did.

1437
01:40:58,487 --> 01:41:02,655
Yet, despite that fear, despite
that risk to your life...

1438
01:41:02,864 --> 01:41:06,990
...you looked at their
faces as they left?

1439
01:41:07,741 --> 01:41:09,700
-Yes, I did.
-Is that correct?

1440
01:41:11,452 --> 01:41:12,118
Yes, I did.

1441
01:41:13,035 --> 01:41:15,202
Did you look at their faces?
Did you really...

1442
01:41:15,870 --> 01:41:19,203
...really look, Mrs. Salinas?

1443
01:41:19,621 --> 01:41:22,955
I glanced at them when they
walked by, but I did see them!

1444
01:41:23,331 --> 01:41:27,123
You...glanced?
You didn't look?

1445
01:41:28,291 --> 01:41:29,375
I saw them!

1446
01:41:30,584 --> 01:41:34,835
You glanced at them, Mrs. Salinas.
You glanced at them through the eyes...

1447
01:41:35,169 --> 01:41:39,836
...of a very frightened woman who
maybe had too much to drink.

1448
01:41:40,837 --> 01:41:43,464
-Objection, Your Honor.
-There is no need, Your Honor.

1449
01:41:43,589 --> 01:41:44,964
I have no further questions.

1450
01:41:45,172 --> 01:41:47,590
Thank you, Mrs. Salinas.
You may step down.

1451
01:41:51,675 --> 01:41:53,509
It was 6:15 on Sunday morning.

1452
01:41:53,717 --> 01:41:57,092
Frank Magicco worked out of
a homicide unit in Brooklyn.

1453
01:41:57,385 --> 01:42:00,386
He was a first grade detective with
an honest name and a solid reputation.

1454
01:42:01,053 --> 01:42:02,596
He was also King Benny's nephew.

1455
01:42:03,513 --> 01:42:05,554
Nick Davenport
was with Internal Affairs.

1456
01:42:06,515 --> 01:42:09,183
He was ambitious and wanted to make
captain before he hit forty.

1457
01:42:09,599 --> 01:42:11,849
He knew the fastest way up
the track was to reel in a...

1458
01:42:12,017 --> 01:42:14,768
...maximum amount of dirty cops
in a minimum amount of time.

1459
01:42:15,433 --> 01:42:16,768
Frank, what is this shit?

1460
01:42:17,268 --> 01:42:18,977
If I were you, I'd do what the kid says.

1461
01:42:19,726 --> 01:42:20,478
You make this one...

1462
01:42:20,561 --> 01:42:22,686
...you're gonna be having breakfast
once a month with the Commissioner.

1463
01:42:22,937 --> 01:42:26,357
You know, you got a real hard-on for this
Styler guy. What's your beef with him?

1464
01:42:26,521 --> 01:42:28,689
-One more thing.
-I can't wait.

1465
01:42:28,856 --> 01:42:33,525
It's simple. No one knows who fed you
this information. And I mean, nobody.

1466
01:42:33,857 --> 01:42:34,733
How did you get it?

1467
01:42:34,901 --> 01:42:38,234
It fell into my lap...just like
it's gonna fall into yours.

1468
01:42:45,528 --> 01:42:46,863
Christ Almighty!

1469
01:42:54,575 --> 01:42:55,950
You got everything in
here but a confession.

1470
01:42:56,117 --> 01:42:57,701
I thought I'd leave that up to you.

1471
01:42:58,075 --> 01:42:59,743
My preference is that
you beat it out of him.

1472
01:42:59,909 --> 01:43:01,410
There's even surveillance photos.

1473
01:43:02,285 --> 01:43:05,329
This piece of shit's pulling in about
five grand a month, ripping off pushers.

1474
01:43:05,411 --> 01:43:06,829
Has been for about 3 years.

1475
01:43:07,122 --> 01:43:09,039
-More like 4.
-He ain't gonna see 5.

1476
01:43:09,164 --> 01:43:10,541
So, you got enough for conviction?

1477
01:43:10,622 --> 01:43:12,749
That ain't up to me.
That's up to a jury.

1478
01:43:16,415 --> 01:43:17,750
Show the jury this.

1479
01:43:20,833 --> 01:43:21,837
What do you got there, Ness?

1480
01:43:22,253 --> 01:43:24,629
About 3 weeks ago,
the body of a drug dealer...

1481
01:43:24,796 --> 01:43:28,003
...named Indian Red Lpez was found
in an alley in Jackson Heights.

1482
01:43:28,588 --> 01:43:30,422
Three bullets in his head,
nothing in his pockets.

1483
01:43:30,505 --> 01:43:31,422
I'm with you so far.

1484
01:43:31,922 --> 01:43:34,341
This is the gun that killed him,
and these are the shells.

1485
01:43:35,006 --> 01:43:37,924
What's behind door number 3?

1486
01:43:38,634 --> 01:43:40,802
The prints on the gun
belong to Adam Styler.

1487
01:43:45,136 --> 01:43:47,137
-Hey, do me a favor, would you?
-What's that?

1488
01:43:47,304 --> 01:43:49,304
If I ever make it onto your
shit list, give me a call.

1489
01:43:50,388 --> 01:43:52,097
Give me a chance to apologize.

1490
01:43:53,013 --> 01:43:56,723
So, you need anything else, you talk to
Frank. He knows how to get a hold of me.

1491
01:43:57,099 --> 01:44:00,226
Take care of yourself, kid.
Water gets choppy out your way.

1492
01:44:00,642 --> 01:44:01,684
I'll do what I can.

1493
01:44:03,476 --> 01:44:06,812
Hey, Ness...did you ever
think of becoming a cop?

1494
01:44:07,979 --> 01:44:09,104
And leave the good guys?

1495
01:44:27,194 --> 01:44:28,528
The body of Christ.

1496
01:44:52,912 --> 01:44:54,079
The body of Christ.

1497
01:44:57,832 --> 01:44:59,832
Michael had done all
that could be expected...

1498
01:45:00,000 --> 01:45:02,834
...of an Assistant District Attorney
seeking a conviction.

1499
01:45:03,584 --> 01:45:07,835
He had a forensic expert detail the make
and caliber of the gun that killed Nokes.

1500
01:45:08,334 --> 01:45:10,752
He just never had the murder
weapon to present as evidence.

1501
01:45:10,918 --> 01:45:13,171
And he never gave the jury
a motive for the murder.

1502
01:45:15,046 --> 01:45:17,381
The tension of his task,
the hours he was working...

1503
01:45:17,715 --> 01:45:20,175
...and the uncertainty about
the outcome weighed heavily on him.

1504
01:45:20,591 --> 01:45:21,716
Did you see their faces?

1505
01:45:22,174 --> 01:45:24,966
Yes, I looked at them,
and they looked at me.

1506
01:45:25,092 --> 01:45:26,176
Did they say anything to you?

1507
01:45:26,425 --> 01:45:29,051
No, they just looked at me
and walked out of McHale's.

1508
01:45:29,217 --> 01:45:31,386
Are you sure the two
defendants killed Sean Nokes?

1509
01:45:31,553 --> 01:45:32,678
I know they killed him.

1510
01:45:33,386 --> 01:45:35,680
If the plan worked, it would
be everyone's success.

1511
01:45:36,387 --> 01:45:38,389
If it failed, the fault
would fall to Michael.

1512
01:45:41,890 --> 01:45:45,892
Father Bobby Carillo, the priest with
the best hook shot on the West Side...

1513
01:45:46,100 --> 01:45:49,685
...remained the key to a plan that called
for all involved to get away with murder.

1514
01:45:50,642 --> 01:45:53,979
Did you turn around, look behind you,
when you heard the shooting, Mr. Carson?

1515
01:45:54,229 --> 01:45:55,813
Why didn't you turn around, Mr. Carson?

1516
01:45:56,062 --> 01:45:58,897
I was concerned for my
companion's safety.

1517
01:45:59,063 --> 01:46:00,898
Mr. Carson, did the two individuals
threaten you in any way?

1518
01:46:02,064 --> 01:46:05,024
Did they threaten anyone
in McHale's Restaurant...?

1519
01:46:06,859 --> 01:46:08,193
I didn't see it, but I know it!

1520
01:46:08,734 --> 01:46:11,027
If you didn't see the defendant
shoot the guard...

1521
01:46:11,111 --> 01:46:13,360
...then how do you know it was
the defendant that shot him?

1522
01:46:37,162 --> 01:46:38,330
So, what's the emergency?

1523
01:46:42,955 --> 01:46:44,747
Shakes shouldn't have sent you.
It's too risky.

1524
01:46:44,956 --> 01:46:48,291
Hey, nobody sent me.
I wanted to see you.

1525
01:46:50,292 --> 01:46:51,167
Why?

1526
01:46:52,877 --> 01:46:55,169
Shakes met with Father Bobby
2 weeks ago.

1527
01:46:55,836 --> 01:46:58,837
-He hasn't heard from him since.
-It's not an overnight decision for him.

1528
01:47:03,130 --> 01:47:06,131
-What if he doesn't testify?
-Then we got a very serious problem.

1529
01:47:22,222 --> 01:47:24,222
Have Shakes talk to Father Bobby again.

1530
01:47:25,972 --> 01:47:29,183
Have him tell him the whole story.
He'll know what that means.

1531
01:47:30,100 --> 01:47:31,226
He already has.

1532
01:47:32,810 --> 01:47:33,683
What?!

1533
01:47:35,017 --> 01:47:38,645
I...was with him when he
talked to Father Bobby.

1534
01:47:41,853 --> 01:47:43,397
I heard everything, Michael.

1535
01:47:53,608 --> 01:47:54,694
So, you know.

1536
01:48:02,947 --> 01:48:04,364
If only you told me.

1537
01:48:09,448 --> 01:48:11,241
I think things could've been different.

1538
01:48:13,950 --> 01:48:15,326
If you could've talked.

1539
01:48:20,536 --> 01:48:22,537
Maybe...maybe we...

1540
01:48:26,747 --> 01:48:27,706
Maybe....

1541
01:48:53,257 --> 01:48:55,675
Carmen, that diet is working.
I don't care what anybody says.

1542
01:48:58,301 --> 01:49:00,134
You still have a thing for Doris Day.

1543
01:49:00,593 --> 01:49:04,637
She was a good woman.
You know the strega?

1544
01:49:05,929 --> 01:49:08,388
It's hard to miss a lady with
four warts and only one eye.

1545
01:49:09,305 --> 01:49:11,597
She needs the heads.

1546
01:49:17,266 --> 01:49:18,599
Take this to the witch.

1547
01:49:20,311 --> 01:49:21,893
Now, why does she need that?

1548
01:49:22,020 --> 01:49:24,937
-She takes the eyes.
-Wonderful!

1549
01:49:25,145 --> 01:49:28,645
Puts them in a bowl and mixes
them with water and oil.

1550
01:49:29,188 --> 01:49:30,021
And then?

1551
01:49:32,106 --> 01:49:36,399
People get headaches, they go to her.
She looks into their eyes...

1552
01:49:36,606 --> 01:49:39,609
...and tells them who is
wishing the headaches.

1553
01:49:40,235 --> 01:49:43,776
She says a few words, and
the headaches go away.

1554
01:49:44,444 --> 01:49:48,779
Once in a while, the person who
wished the headaches, goes away too.

1555
01:49:49,612 --> 01:49:53,114
This guy, Addison, the one
who works for the Mayor...

1556
01:49:53,280 --> 01:49:55,406
...he quits his job in 2 weeks.

1557
01:49:56,616 --> 01:50:00,117
He don't want nobody to know
what kind of a guy he is.

1558
01:50:00,326 --> 01:50:03,493
He don't want nobody to see
pictures of him they shouldn't see.

1559
01:50:04,993 --> 01:50:06,578
-He knows this?
-He will.

1560
01:50:08,037 --> 01:50:10,829
The boys he buys for
parties are expensive.

1561
01:50:10,996 --> 01:50:14,331
Now, Addison makes good money,
but he don't make real money.

1562
01:50:15,664 --> 01:50:16,832
How much does he owe?

1563
01:50:17,000 --> 01:50:21,000
Eight grand with a heavy vig.
I paid that off.

1564
01:50:21,168 --> 01:50:25,461
-You paid?
-Addison's debts belong to me now.

1565
01:50:27,085 --> 01:50:29,587
-You hate debts.
-I hate Addison!

1566
01:50:32,379 --> 01:50:35,590
We're in the dirty end of the field now.
That's where I play.

1567
01:50:36,006 --> 01:50:37,715
And I like to play alone.

1568
01:50:38,382 --> 01:50:42,926
You're a nice kid. You always were.
Don't let this change it.

1569
01:50:56,222 --> 01:51:00,642
His mother named him Edward Goldenberg
Robinson, after her favorite actor.

1570
01:51:01,515 --> 01:51:02,849
To continue the Hollywood connection...

1571
01:51:02,890 --> 01:51:05,516
Eddie Robinson took the street name
"Little Caesar"...

1572
01:51:06,100 --> 01:51:09,018
...as he made his way up the ranks
of the lucrative drug trade.

1573
01:51:09,603 --> 01:51:12,729
He had a 12-year-old son in a
private school in upstate New York.

1574
01:51:13,563 --> 01:51:15,521
He named him Rizzo,
after his youngest brother...

1575
01:51:15,730 --> 01:51:19,148
...who died while in the custody
of the Wilkinson Home for Boys.

1576
01:51:19,897 --> 01:51:23,066
-I want you to give me some money.
-All right.

1577
01:51:23,609 --> 01:51:26,942
I'll play along.
How long before you pay it back?

1578
01:51:27,443 --> 01:51:30,778
I ain't paying it back.
Somebody else is.

1579
01:51:33,404 --> 01:51:34,738
This somebody I know?

1580
01:51:35,072 --> 01:51:38,404
-Your little brother knew him.
-Rizzo?

1581
01:51:41,156 --> 01:51:42,406
How did he know Rizzo?

1582
01:51:43,032 --> 01:51:47,450
Henry Addison was a guard
in an upstate reform school.

1583
01:51:47,743 --> 01:51:52,079
He was there the same time as Rizzo,
before and after he died.

1584
01:51:57,914 --> 01:52:00,456
Count out $8,000.
Put it in an envelope.

1585
01:52:04,457 --> 01:52:08,583
You...go back a long time, old man.

1586
01:52:10,001 --> 01:52:11,460
Old men always do.

1587
01:52:11,920 --> 01:52:14,711
Ran with the guineas, back
when the guineas were tough.

1588
01:52:14,753 --> 01:52:16,087
I ran when I could.

1589
01:52:17,337 --> 01:52:18,797
Looked good doing it, too.

1590
01:52:21,714 --> 01:52:25,715
Gave the business some style, some class.

1591
01:52:27,466 --> 01:52:30,467
Made it a call for respect, the way
you wore it...the way you talked it.

1592
01:52:32,093 --> 01:52:34,095
I always liked that about you.

1593
01:52:34,636 --> 01:52:37,971
I'm no help to you.
My tailor is dead.

1594
01:52:44,973 --> 01:52:49,308
I'll look up our friend and
collect the money he owes me.

1595
01:52:49,600 --> 01:52:51,601
He owes you something more than money.

1596
01:52:52,143 --> 01:52:54,060
Ain't nothing worth more than the green.

1597
01:52:54,560 --> 01:52:57,312
-This is.
-What, old man?

1598
01:52:58,312 --> 01:53:00,520
What's this guy owe that
means more than dollars?

1599
01:53:01,062 --> 01:53:05,022
He owes you Rizzo. He's the man
that killed your brother.

1600
01:53:14,235 --> 01:53:16,361
They said he died of pneumonia.

1601
01:53:17,319 --> 01:53:17,987
They said.

1602
01:53:25,322 --> 01:53:26,990
What is the relevance of this?

1603
01:53:27,490 --> 01:53:30,158
So, Ralph Ferguson is
a Sunday school teacher?

1604
01:53:30,366 --> 01:53:33,159
I don't know, counsel.
What you're asking is highly unusual.

1605
01:53:34,034 --> 01:53:38,202
I understand that, Your Honor. Again,
I need to put a face to the victim.

1606
01:53:39,370 --> 01:53:42,204
Otherwise it's just another
name in the obituaries.

1607
01:53:42,911 --> 01:53:44,999
Mr. Snyder, any objections?

1608
01:53:47,165 --> 01:53:48,456
I don't have a problem with that.

1609
01:53:49,748 --> 01:53:53,083
Your Honor, the prosecution would like
to call Ralph Ferguson to the stand.

1610
01:54:19,676 --> 01:54:21,762
-Good morning, Mr. Ferguson.
-Good morning.

1611
01:54:22,470 --> 01:54:25,387
I'd like to thank you for coming, I
understand it's been a long trip for you.

1612
01:54:26,347 --> 01:54:28,305
I'm just sorry it had to be
for something like this.

1613
01:54:29,764 --> 01:54:32,141
You and the victim, Sean Nokes,
were such good friends.

1614
01:54:32,306 --> 01:54:34,974
I think your testimony as a character
witness will be very valuable.

1615
01:54:35,223 --> 01:54:37,892
We were great friends. It would
be hard to find a better friend.

1616
01:54:38,851 --> 01:54:42,644
-Would you say you were his best friend?
-I was his closest, that's for sure.

1617
01:54:43,436 --> 01:54:47,396
-How long did you know each other?
-About 17, 18 years.

1618
01:54:48,188 --> 01:54:49,521
And did you see each other often?

1619
01:54:50,023 --> 01:54:54,441
As often as we could...
weekends, holidays, vacations.

1620
01:54:56,358 --> 01:54:59,943
-What kind of man was Sean Nokes?
-He was a good man.

1621
01:55:00,319 --> 01:55:02,527
He was too good to be shot dead
by a couple of street punks.

1622
01:55:03,154 --> 01:55:05,528
Objection, Your Honor, statement
is one of opinion not fact.

1623
01:55:05,780 --> 01:55:06,945
He was asked his opinion.

1624
01:55:07,155 --> 01:55:09,280
Overruled. Please proceed.

1625
01:55:11,031 --> 01:55:15,324
Mr. Ferguson...were you aware of
any enemies he might have had?

1626
01:55:15,699 --> 01:55:17,449
Sean Nokes had no enemies.

1627
01:55:18,201 --> 01:55:21,535
Thank you, Mr. Ferguson.
I have no further questions.

1628
01:55:26,286 --> 01:55:27,788
Is that a prison?

1629
01:55:27,954 --> 01:55:30,330
No, it's a juvenile
facility for young boys.

1630
01:55:30,413 --> 01:55:33,414
Your function was what at this facility?

1631
01:55:33,540 --> 01:55:35,290
Standard stuff.

1632
01:55:35,457 --> 01:55:39,542
Keep the boys in line, make sure
they got to classes on time....

1633
01:55:40,292 --> 01:55:42,793
Keep an eye out for trouble,
put them down for the night.

1634
01:55:43,877 --> 01:55:47,629
As guards, were you and
Mr. Nokes allowed to use force to...

1635
01:55:47,796 --> 01:55:49,796
...as you put it,
"keep the boys in line"?

1636
01:55:50,379 --> 01:55:52,379
What...what do you mean, force?

1637
01:55:52,547 --> 01:55:53,423
Were you allowed to hit them?

1638
01:55:55,672 --> 01:55:56,548
Of course not.

1639
01:55:56,883 --> 01:56:00,675
Were any of the boys hit by any of the
guards any time at the Wilkinson home?

1640
01:56:02,217 --> 01:56:05,176
I'm sure something like that
may have happened. It was a...

1641
01:56:05,844 --> 01:56:09,179
...big place, but it wasn't
the common practice.

1642
01:56:09,345 --> 01:56:10,678
Let's narrow the place down.

1643
01:56:10,845 --> 01:56:14,223
Did you or Mr. Nokes ever hit any
of the boys under your care...

1644
01:56:14,390 --> 01:56:16,847
...at the Wilkinson Home for Boys?

1645
01:56:24,602 --> 01:56:27,060
Would you like me to
repeat the question?

1646
01:56:27,268 --> 01:56:28,185
No.

1647
01:56:30,269 --> 01:56:32,396
Then answer it, please.
And remember, you're under oath.

1648
01:56:33,438 --> 01:56:36,522
A few of the boys who we considered
to be discipline problems...

1649
01:56:36,689 --> 01:56:38,690
...were hit on occasion.

1650
01:56:38,900 --> 01:56:40,400
And how were they hit?

1651
01:56:40,608 --> 01:56:42,441
-I don't know what you mean.
-A fist?

1652
01:56:42,942 --> 01:56:46,776
Open hand? Kick? Baton, maybe?

1653
01:56:47,486 --> 01:56:51,194
-Depends on what the situation called for.
-Who determined that situation?

1654
01:56:51,737 --> 01:56:52,613
The guard on the scene.

1655
01:56:53,364 --> 01:56:55,363
That's a lot of power to
have over a boy, isn't it?

1656
01:56:55,864 --> 01:56:59,448
-It came with the job, sir.
-Did torture come with the job?

1657
01:57:08,743 --> 01:57:11,204
